<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-487-237  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 487 237.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  Sept 14 1990* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Fujitsu branches out into fault tolerant market. (Fujitsu Ltd.'sSure System 2000 computer system) (product announcement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Takahashi, Ken.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Fujitsu Ltd. (product introduction).andO;Product:   Fujitsu Sure System 2000 (Computer system) (product introduction).andO;Topic:     Product IntroductionFault ToleranceComputer SystemsComputer industry.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>FUJITSU BRANCHES OUT INTO FAULT TOLERANT MARKET TOKYO, JAPAN, 1990 SEP 14(NB) -- Fujitsu, Japan's computer giant, has introduced a communicationprocessor which maintains continuous operation of a computer system toprovide fault-tolerance with both hardware and software.andM;Fujitsu's fault-tolerant processor, Sure System 2000, allows fault-tolerancefor networked host computers.andP;  In case one of them causes trouble, theprocessor instantly allots the task to another host computer.andP;  Fujitsu claimsthat its processor will allow users to amend software without stopping thesystem.andM;The processor incorporates 32-bit Gmicro 300 TRON processors, high-speed 4 MB(megabyte) DRAM (dynamic random access memory) memories and a logic LSI(large-scale integrated circuit) with 100,000-gate CMOS (complimentary metaloxide semiconductor) gate arrays.andP;  Moreover, Fujitsu has realized multipleProcessor Modules (PMs), each of which can process each task in parallel.andO;From two to six PMs can be mounted, each with its own independent centralprocessor.andP;  Each PM incorporates its own 16 MB or 32 MB memory.andM;The operating system software called SXO for the Sure System 2000 allowsvarious software units to be distributed across the available PMs and ensuresthat in case software problems occur, backup software will provide continuousoperation and total system failure will be prevented.andM;Fujitsu projects sales of 2,000 fault-tolerant systems over three years.andO;One-quarter will be overseas - mainly to Australia, Spain, South Korea andSoutheast Asia, where many Fujitsu computers are installed.andM;Hardware will rent for 1.35 million yen ($9,640) a month, with the softwarepriced at 235,000 yen ($1,680) monthly.andP;  Both will be available around nextsummer.andM;Currently in the Japanese market, U.S.andP;  fault-tolerant computer makers suchas California-based Tandem Computers and Massachusetts- based StratusComputer dominate the Japanese FTC market.andP;  Fault- tolerant computers havehigh levels of back-up facilities to ensure smooth operation even whenportions of a system fail.andP;  They are essential for networks used in banking,air traffic control, and other fields where failures could cause severefinancial or safety problems.andM;(Ken Takahashi/19900913/Press Contact: Fujitsu Ltd., 03-216-3211)</TEXT></DOC>